<p class="p">
 <italic class="italic">Mort</italic> was calculated only for the warm season (
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M50" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">1</mn>
    <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
    <mtext class="mtext">April</mtext>
    <mo class="mo">–</mo>
    <mn class="mn">30</mn>
    <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
    <mtext class="mtext">September</mtext>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) because the ERFs were derived for these months only (
 <xref rid="c4" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Baccini et al. 2008</xref>). 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M51" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> was then calculated by converting 
 <italic class="italic">Mort</italic> into a mortality rate (per 100,000, using Pop) and then subtracting it for the present-day time period from the estimate for the future time period.
</p>
